  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects of AML regulations typically include:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Conduct due diligence on customers\n\n2. Established in many countries through laws like:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (United States)\n- Money Laundering Regulations (United Kingdom)\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n\n3. Covering various financial sectors:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Money transfer services\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThese regulations aim to combat financial crimes like drug trafficking, terrorism financing, and tax evasion by making it harder to hide the origins of illegal funds.",
